conditions.name: Viral Upper Respiratory Infection (Common Cold)
pearls: Viral URIs are self-limited; antibiotics are not indicated.
Symptom overlap with influenza/COVID-19 is common; consider epidemiology.
studyTreatment: Supportive care: hydration, rest, antipyretics/analgesics (per local dosing guidelines)
Return/seek care if red flags develop

conditions.name: Influenza
pearls: Abrupt onset fever, myalgia, and headache are typical.
Consider antivirals for high‑risk per guidelines.
studyTreatment: Antivirals for high‑risk or severe disease (verify local guidance)

conditions.name: COVID‑19
pearls: Loss of smell/taste increases likelihood.
Test to confirm; follow public health guidance.

conditions.name: Community‑Acquired Pneumonia
pearls: Pleuritic chest pain and focal findings suggest consolidation.
Assess severity scores in practice (e.g., CURB‑65)
studyTreatment: Empiric antibiotics per local guidelines if clinical diagnosis

conditions.name: Uncomplicated Urinary Tract Infection
pearls: Dysuria + frequency without vaginal symptoms raises probability.
Consider pregnancy status and local resistance patterns.
studyTreatment: First‑line oral options vary by region; verify local antibiogram

conditions.name: Dengue Fever
pearls: Watch for warning signs around defervescence (days 3–7).
Avoid NSAIDs if bleeding risk; confirm with labs in practice.

conditions.name: Malaria (falciparum/non‑falciparum)
pearls: Consider travel/residence in endemic area; test with smear/RDT.
Severe malaria is a medical emergency.
studyTreatment: Antimalarial regimen depends on species/resistance; follow national guidelines

conditions.name: Acute Appendicitis
pearls: Periumbilical pain migrating to RLQ is classic but not universal.
Rebound/guarding suggest peritonitis; surgical consult in practice.
studyTreatment: Keep NPO, IV fluids; surgical referral when suspected

conditions.name: Acute Gastroenteritis
pearls: Most cases are viral and self‑limited.
Assess dehydration.

conditions.name: Asthma
pearls: Variable, reversible airflow obstruction
Often worse at night/early morning

conditions.name: Acute Coronary Syndrome (MI/UA)
pearls: Crushing chest pain radiating to arm/jaw; risk factors matter.
studyTreatment: Immediate emergency evaluation; this app is educational only
